column1: Styling errors on mobile
column28:
h1. The form and carousel are breaking again on very narrow displays.

Fixed successfully: changing the width of the component dynamically via React using useEffect() to trigger the render of the carousel after the initial render in order to avoid the glitchy view. The form has been given a fixed view height value and percentage to make sure it’s always in the display.

column1: NavMenu Hover Bug
NavMenu scroll bug
column28:
h1. The menu isn't on the page but on top of the page, making it scrollable

Reason: The position was set to relative.

Fix: Changed the menu to Position: fixed in order for it stay on screen regardless of scroll, just like the parent website.

column1: Transition
Scrolling bug
column28:
When navigating between pages the scroll was automatic from the last page.

Reason: Due to the nature of React it wasn’t exactly a new page but a re-render.

Fix: Created a custom hook that scrolls back to the top on navigation.

column1: Create UML diagrams for the project in the context of the kick off meeting.
column28: A UML diagram is a diagram based on the UML (Unified Modeling Language) with the purpose of visually representing a system along with its main actors, roles, actions, artifacts or classes, in order to better understand, alter, maintain, or document information about the system.

column1: Creating a sequence diagram in context of kickoff meeting.
column28: A sequence diagram or system sequence diagram shows process interactions arranged in time sequence in the field of software engineering. It depicts the processes involved and the sequence of messages exchanged between the processes needed to carry out the functionality.

column1: Creating a USE CASE diagram in context of kickoff meeting.
column28: A use case diagram is a graphical depiction of a user's possible interactions with a system. A use case diagram shows various use cases and different types of users the system has and will often be accompanied by other types of diagrams as well. The use cases are represented by either circles or ellipses.
